Task 1: Understanding User and Group Management Fundamentals
Subtask 1.1: Examine Current User and Group Information
First, let's explore the current user and group configuration on your system.

Step 1: Check your current user information

whoami
id
Step 2: View the user database file

cat /etc/passwd
Step 3: Examine the group database file

cat /etc/group
Step 4: Check the shadow password file (requires sudo)

sudo cat /etc/shadow
Subtask 1.2: Understanding File Structure
Step 1: Analyze the passwd file format

head -5 /etc/passwd
echo "Format: username:password:UID:GID:GECOS:home_directory:shell"
Step 2: Examine group file structure

head -5 /etc/group
echo "Format: group_name:password:GID:user_list"
Task 2: User Account Management with useradd, usermod, and userdel
Subtask 2.1: Creating New Users with useradd
Step 1: Create a basic user account

sudo useradd john
Step 2: Verify the user was created

grep john /etc/passwd
id john
Step 3: Create a user with specific options

sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash -c "Jane Smith" -G users jane
Step 4: Create a user with custom home directory

sudo useradd -m -d /home/custom_mike -s /bin/bash mike
Step 5: Set passwords for the new users

sudo passwd john
sudo passwd jane
sudo passwd mike
Step 6: Create a system user (for services)

sudo useradd -r -s /bin/false serviceuser
Subtask 2.2: Modifying Users with usermod
Step 1: Change user's login shell

sudo usermod -s /bin/zsh john
grep john /etc/passwd
Step 2: Modify user's home directory

sudo usermod -d /home/john_new -m john
ls -la /home/ | grep john
Step 3: Change user's full name (GECOS field)

sudo usermod -c "John Doe - Developer" john
grep john /etc/passwd
Step 4: Lock a user account

sudo usermod -L mike
sudo passwd -S mike
Step 5: Unlock the user account

sudo usermod -U mike
sudo passwd -S mike
Step 6: Change user's UID

sudo usermod -u 1500 jane
id jane
Subtask 2.3: Deleting Users with userdel
Step 1: Delete a user without removing home directory

sudo userdel serviceuser
grep serviceuser /etc/passwd || echo "User serviceuser deleted"
Step 2: Delete a user and remove home directory

sudo userdel -r mike
ls /home/ | grep mike || echo "Mike's home directory removed"
Step 3: Force delete a user (if logged in)

sudo userdel -f john 2>/dev/null || echo "User john deleted or not found"
Task 3: Group Management with groupadd, groupdel, and usermod -aG
Subtask 3.1: Creating Groups with groupadd
Step 1: Create a basic group

sudo groupadd developers
Step 2: Verify group creation

grep developers /etc/group
getent group developers
Step 3: Create a group with specific GID

sudo groupadd -g 2000 managers
Step 4: Create a system group

sudo groupadd -r systemgroup
Step 5: View all created groups

grep -E "(developers|managers|systemgroup)" /etc/group
Subtask 3.2: Managing Group Memberships with usermod -aG
Step 1: Add jane to the developers group

sudo usermod -aG developers jane
Step 2: Verify group membership

groups jane
id jane
Step 3: Add jane to multiple groups

sudo usermod -aG managers,users jane
groups jane
Step 4: Create a new user and add to groups simultaneously

sudo useradd -m -G developers,users alice
groups alice
Step 5: Set a primary group for a user

sudo usermod -g developers alice
id alice
Subtask 3.3: Advanced Group Management
Step 1: Create a project-specific group and users

sudo groupadd project_alpha
sudo useradd -m -G project_alpha bob
sudo useradd -m -G project_alpha carol
Step 2: Verify project team setup

getent group project_alpha
Step 3: Remove user from a group

sudo gpasswd -d jane managers
groups jane
Step 4: Add user back to group using gpasswd

sudo gpasswd -a jane managers
groups jane
Subtask 3.4: Deleting Groups with groupdel
Step 1: Try to delete a group that's a primary group (will fail)

sudo groupdel developers || echo "Cannot delete primary group"
Step 2: Change primary group first, then delete

sudo usermod -g users alice
sudo groupdel developers
Step 3: Delete unused groups

sudo groupdel systemgroup
sudo groupdel project_alpha
Step 4: Verify group deletion

grep -E "(systemgroup|project_alpha)" /etc/group || echo "Groups successfully deleted"
Task 4: Practical User and Group Management Scenarios
Subtask 4.1: Setting Up a Development Team
Step 1: Create development groups

sudo groupadd webdev
sudo groupadd database
sudo groupadd devops
Step 2: Create team members

sudo useradd -m -G webdev,users -s /bin/bash sarah
sudo useradd -m -G database,users -s /bin/bash david
sudo useradd -m -G devops,users -s /bin/bash lisa
Step 3: Set passwords for team members

echo "Setting passwords for team members..."
sudo passwd sarah
sudo passwd david
sudo passwd lisa
Step 4: Create a shared project directory

sudo mkdir -p /opt/projects
sudo chgrp webdev /opt/projects
sudo chmod 775 /opt/projects
Subtask 4.2: Managing User Account Policies
Step 1: Set password aging for a user

sudo chage -M 90 -m 7 -W 14 sarah
Step 2: View password aging information

sudo chage -l sarah
Step 3: Set account expiration date

sudo usermod -e 2024-12-31 david
Step 4: Check account status

sudo chage -l david
Subtask 4.3: Bulk User Operations
Step 1: Create a script for bulk user creation

cat > create_users.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
users=("intern1" "intern2" "intern3")
for user in "${users[@]}"; do
    sudo useradd -m -G users -s /bin/bash "$user"
    echo "Created user: $user"
done
EOF
Step 2: Make script executable and run it

chmod +x create_users.sh
./create_users.sh
Step 3: Verify bulk creation

grep -E "(intern1|intern2|intern3)" /etc/passwd
Step 4: Set temporary passwords for interns

for user in intern1 intern2 intern3; do
    echo "$user:temp123" | sudo chpasswd
    sudo chage -d 0 "$user"  # Force password change on first login
done
Task 5: Security and Best Practices
Subtask 5.1: Implementing Security Measures
Step 1: Check for users with empty passwords

sudo awk -F: '($2 == "") {print $1}' /etc/shadow
Step 2: Find users with UID 0 (root privileges)

awk -F: '($3 == 0) {print $1}' /etc/passwd
Step 3: List users with login shells

grep -E "(bash|zsh|sh)$" /etc/passwd
Step 4: Check for duplicate UIDs

cut -d: -f3 /etc/passwd | sort | uniq -d
Subtask 5.2: Monitoring and Auditing
Step 1: Check last login information

lastlog | head -10
Step 2: View currently logged in users

who
w
Step 3: Check user login history

last | head -10
Step 4: Monitor failed login attempts

sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log | tail -5 || echo "No recent failed attempts"
